Part 6

I didn't know any of this when it actually happened. 

Vikram never told me the story of that board meeting, or the double exposure on the glass window, or Ira Sen's name. Not once. Not even later when we were old men sitting on the hospital bench and had run out of things to hide from each other. 

I pieced the story together the way you piece together most of a friend's life that you weren't present for. I gathered it from a stray line here, a name mentioned once in passing and never again, a nurse's file at the clinic, and an old clerk who still remembered "Ahuja Sahib" fondly enough to talk to me after the funeral.

Some of it, I admit, I am still guessing at. I will say so plainly when I am.

But what I do know for certain, because he told me this part directly, once, was spoken when we were sitting outside the ICU with two cold cups of tea that neither of us drank.

"I never wanted the business, Adarsh," he had said, his voice flat. "Twice, life decided for me. Not once."

I asked him what he meant by twice.

"1996. Then 2007," he replied. "My father's liver, both times. The first time, it let go of him a little, giving him ten more years. The second time, it didn't."

He didn't explain further, and I didn't ask him to. Some men tell you a raw fact and expect you to sit with it, not chase it with questions. 

I sat with that fact for years before I truly understood what he meant.

Two times, a decade apart, the exact same door had opened and pulled him out of the life he had actually chosen for himself—a stethoscope, a dissecting table, a hostel room, a friend, me. And both times, it had placed him behind a desk he had never asked to sit at. 

Most men would have called that unfair, cursed their luck, and stopped there. 

Vikram didn't run either time. He stood his ground, took the pen, and signed.

I know that much for certain, because I watched what came after, even the parts I didn't fully understand until decades later. 

That was the board meeting. That was the window. 

That, as I would learn only after his death, was also Ira Sen. Her name he mentioned to me exactly once in fifty years, and only in passing, as if checking that the old wound was still there before moving on.

But that was only the beginning. The real test came next.

[End of Part 6]
